		   <br><nobr><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default [2.28]</nobr><br><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Adiemus&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Use your dwarven axe for now. The tentacle whip has a proc (lifetap), but I am reasonably sure that you aren't high enough level to get the proc to go off yet (if you get a message like "Your will is not sufficient to control this weapon", you're not high enough yet).<br><br>A sidebar rant: the level at which some of this stuff procs is, IMHO, ridiculous. Gnoll hide laraits at 25? Would it be so unbalancing for VI to drop that level requirement down to 15 or even 10? A 1.2 second stun isn't all that terrific, even if you are dual-weilding them. Base damage is only 3 points, and they aren't going to proc everytime either.<br><br>If you really want to go ahead and do a weapon upgrade, 50pp should afford you a Combine Longsword or Scimitar, both of which are magical. You buy those from the Gupsies in Oasis of Marr. I have even occasionally seen a Bone Bladed Claymore at that price (from Befallen). With the influx of all the stuff from Kunark, prices on pretty good older stuff has dropped noticibly (BiBS were around 400 6 months ago; now are 175), so that works to your advantage as well.<br><br>Also, Kilraven brings up some excellent points. You get your first spells next level, and they are the first real tangible evidence (aside from Lay on Hands) that you are not just another warrior and are a Paladin. I don't think that your spells will set you back all that much money, but I would definitely set aside any plans to upgrade equipment until you have purchased them all (save for True North- not useless, but close).</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform">